  "answer": "The critic misreads the forbidden case. The clause requires the critic to demonstrate that any two regions shared identical failure sequences at identical chronometric resolution. The target’s own evidence—Ugarit burns c. 1190, Hattusa c. 1180, Mycenaean centers c. 1200–1150—shows precisely the opposite: desynchronized, non-identical failure sequences at different times and durations. The target does not need to provide identical sequences; it needs only to show that the forbidden case does not obtain, which the cited desynchronization does. The critic’s demand that the target disprove a shared variable at coarser resolution is a straw man: the forbidden case is stated at the resolution of identical failure sequences, not coarse-grained similarity. The target’s claim of no unified causal structure is therefore supported by the evidence of heterogeneous timing and trajectories, not undermined by it."
